<Base title="actualfuckingwebsite.com">
  <h1>An actual fucking website.</h1>

  <p>
    You've seen the first one. Raw HTML. No CSS. Just text on a white void. Someone
    very angry on the internet said that was enough, and honestly? Fair point. Text
    is the whole point. The medium is the message, etc.
  </p>

  <p>
    Then someone else came along with seven lines of CSS — a max-width, a font-size,
    some line-height — and said <em>"look how much better it reads now."</em> Also a
    great point. Readability matters. Give words room to breathe.
  </p>

  <p>But here's what both of those websites got wrong.</p>

  <p><strong>They had one page.</strong></p>

  <p>
    One page is not a website. One page is a sticky note. It's a pamphlet you hand
    someone at the airport and then sprint away. It says one thing and it's done
    with you forever.
  </p>

  <p>
    A website has <em>pages</em>. It has an about page so people know you're a human
    and not an AI. It has a blog so your thoughts exist somewhere other than a
    thread on a platform that will be bankrupt, irrelevant, or acquired by a
    bored billionaire by Thursday. It has a <code>/now</code> page because Derek
    Sivers was right. It has a contact page with your email address, because
    how the hell else is anyone supposed to reach you — a contact form that
    sends data to three different analytics companies?
  </p>

  <p>You can have all of that. With a nav that is just a list of links. With a layout that is just centering. With CSS you could read in under a minute.</p>

  <p>This is that website.</p>

  <hr />

  <p>
    Look at that nav up there. Five links. Each one goes to a page. That's it.
    That's the whole architecture. No framework, no hydration boundary, no
    lighthouse score celebration tweet. Just pages.
  </p>

  <p>
    This entire site is under 15KB uncompressed. Your cookie consent banner is
    larger than this website.
  </p>

  <p>
    Go read the <a href="/about">about page</a>. Then come back and tell me we
    need a 200KB JavaScript bundle to display biographical text.
  </p>
</Base>
